SIMPLE: precipitate
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitate
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praecipitatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>praecipitare</ets> to
precipitate, fr. <ets>praeceps</ets> headlong. See
<er>Precipice</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Overhasty; rash; <as>as, the
king was too <ex>precipitate</ex> in declaring war</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lacking due deliberation or care; hurried; said or
done before the time; <as>as, a <ex>precipitate</ex> measure</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧The rapidity of our too <xex>precipitate</xex> course.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Landor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Falling, flowing, or rushing, with steep descent;
headlong.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Precipitate</qex> the furious torrent flows.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Ending quickly in death; brief and fatal; <as>as, a
<ex>precipitate</ex> case of disease</as>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitate
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL.
<ets>praecipitatum</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧cipit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>An
insoluble substance separated from a solution in a concrete state by the
action of some reagent added to the solution, or of some force, such as
heat or cold. The precipitate may fall to the bottom (whence the name),
may be diffused through the solution, or may float at or near the
surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>atmospheric moisture condensed as rain or snow,
etc.; same as <er>precipitation{5}</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Red precipitate</b></col> <fld>(Old. Chem)</fld>,
<cd>mercuric oxide (<chform>HgO</chform>) a heavy red crystalline powder
obtained by heating mercuric nitrate, or by heating mercury in the air.
Prepared in the latter manner, it was the <altname>precipitate per
se</altname> of the alchemists.</cd> -- <col><b>White
precipitate</b></col> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A heavy
white amorphous powder (<chform>NH2.HgCl</chform>) obtained by adding
ammonia to a solution of mercuric chloride or corrosive sublimate; --
formerly called also <altname>infusible white precipitate</altname>, and
now <altname>amido-mercuric chloride</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A
white crystalline substance obtained by adding a solution of corrosive
sublimate to a solution of sal ammoniac (ammonium chloride); -- formerly
called also <altname>fusible white precipitate</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitate
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Precipitated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Precipitating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To throw
headlong; to cast down from a precipice or height.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She and her horse had been <qex>precipitated</qex> to the pebbled
region of the river.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To urge or press on with eager haste or violence; to
cause to happen, or come to a crisis, suddenly or too soon; <as>as,
<ex>precipitate</ex> a journey, or a conflict</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Back to his sight <qex>precipitates</qex> her steps.</q>
<rj><qau>Glover.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If they be daring, it may <qex>precipitate</qex> their designs,
and prove dangerous.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To separate from a solution, or
other medium, in the form of a precipitate; <as>as, water
<ex>precipitates</ex> camphor when in solution with
alcohol</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The light vapor of the preceding evening had been
<qex>precipitated</qex> by the cold.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Precipitate
<hw>Pre*cip"i*tate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dash or
fall headlong.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So many fathom down <qex>precipitating</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hasten without preparation.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To separate from a solution as a
precipitate. See <er>Precipitate</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Precipitately</ent>⟦br⟧
